{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509565"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11435"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11435"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.11,0.75,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109717"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4068"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92114"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1020"},{"type":"tags","id":"1927"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"3996"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109717"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents to his general practitioner to discuss his symptoms of increasing lethargy. He has been reluctant to come in because his friend of similar age recently had her driving licence withdrawn due to her declining health. His medical history includes a myocardial infarction at age 72, stable angina, epilepsy (his last seizure was four years ago), narcolepsy for which he saw a respiratory physician (sleep specialist) four years ago and schizophrenia. His current medications include sublingual nitrate spray, sodium valproate, modafinil and quetiapine. He reports having the sensation to sleep \u0022all of a sudden\u0022 despite taking scheduled naps. On further consultation he admits to having difficulty falling asleep occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refer for onroad practical driving test","Provide temporary clearance until it interferes with driving","Decrease dosage of quetiapine","Refer to a respiratory physician (sleep specialist) for driving clearance","Increase dosage of modafinil"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer to a respiratory physician  (sleep specialist) for driving clearance \u003C/strong\u003Eis the correct answer in this case. A patient with narcolepsy should see a sleep specialist at least annually. Seeing as this patient last saw his sleep specialist four years ago and his new symptoms he should see a sleep specialist for review of his condition and for driving clearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferring for onroad practical driving test \u003C/strong\u003Eis appropriate step to take in the management of this patient\u0027s condition, it is not the immediate next step. Seeing as the patient\u0027s symptoms has changed recently he should see a sleep or respiratory specialist for review of his conditional driving licence\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding temporary clearance until it interferes with driving \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be irresponsible in this case.\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EPatients with narcolepsy are required to have a conditional licence and this patient\u0027s current symptoms of sudden onset somnolence, makes him a danger to himself and others on the road.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChanging medications at this stage would be premature as this patient needs further assessment first:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreasing dosage of quetiapine: \u003C/strong\u003Ewhile it is possible that his quetiapine may be causing his symptoms, he will still require formal review by sleep specialist before a conditional driving licence would be provided to him.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing dosage of modafinil\u003C/strong\u003E: while it is true that modafinil reduces daytime sleepiness, increasing dosage does not necessarily always result in a decrease in daytime sleepiness. There are also varying state laws around who can prescribe modafinil.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Many conditions, if severe, can place restrictions on driving. Patients with narcolepsy must be reviewed by a sleep specialist at least annually and respond well to treatment before being able to drive.","Narcolepsy can significantly impact daily functioning and safety, particularly in activities such as driving, due to sudden onset sleep episodes."],"references":["Assessing Fitness to Drive [Internet]. austroads.com.au. Available from: https://austroads.com.au/drivers-and-vehicles/assessing-fitness-to-drive","Thorpy MJ, Dauvilliers Y. Clinical and practical considerations in the pharmacologic management of narcolepsy. Sleep Med. 2015 Jan;16(1):9-18. doi: 10.1016/j.sleep.2014.10.002. Epub 2014 Oct 16. PMID: 25458251. Available from: Thorpy MJ, Dauvilliers Y. Clinical and practical considerations in the pharmacologic management of narcolepsy. Sleep Med. 2015 Jan;16(1):9-18. doi: 10.1016/j.sleep.2014.10.002. Epub 2014 Oct 16. PMID: 25458251.","McNicholas WT, Rodenstein D. Sleep apnoea and driving risk: the need for regulation. Eur Respir Rev. 2015 Dec;24(138):602-6. doi: 10.1183/16000617.0049-2015. PMID: 26621974; PMCID: PMC9487626. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26621974/","Bonsignore MR, Randerath W, Schiza S, Verbraecken J, Elliott MW, Riha R, Barbe F, Bouloukaki I, Castrogiovanni A, Deleanu O, Goncalves M, Leger D, Marrone O, Penzel T, Ryan S, Smyth D, Teran-Santos J, Turino C, McNicholas WT. European Respiratory Society statement on sleep apnoea, sleepiness and driving risk. Eur Respir J. 2021 Feb 25;57(2):2001272. doi: 10.1183/13993003.01272-2020. PMID: 33008939. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33008939/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92114"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11435"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92114"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T17:43:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T17:45:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4068"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109717"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro